This is a list detailing the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) listings situated within the [Chugach Census Area](/Chugach_Census_Area,_Alaska) of [Alaska](/Alaska), United States. For those unfamiliar, the [Chugach Census Area](/Chugach_Census_Area,_Alaska) was created in 2019 from a portion of the former [Valdez-Cordova Census Area](/Valdez-Cordova_Census_Area,_Alaska), inheriting its rugged coastline, vast wilderness, and a smattering of human endeavors deemed worthy of preservation. One might ponder the cosmic irony of attempting to preserve fleeting human imprints against the backdrop of such an indifferent, ancient landscape, but here we are.

This compilation aims to provide a complete, if somewhat futile, inventory of the properties and districts that have been deemed significant enough by the [National Park Service](/National_Park_Service) to warrant inclusion on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) within this particular corner of [Alaska](/Alaska). The geographical coordinates provided for these registered properties and districts are included below, allowing for their precise, if perhaps unnecessary, visualization on a digital map. &#91;1&#93;

Currently, the [Chugach Census Area](/Chugach_Census_Area,_Alaska) boasts 10 properties and districts prominently listed on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places). Among these, a select few—two, to be exact—have achieved the elevated status of [National Historic Landmarks](/National_Historic_Landmark), signifying their exceptional national importance. In the grand scheme of things, it’s a small collection, yet each entry offers a glimpse into the tenacious, often misguided, history of human activity in an environment that consistently reminds us of our own insignificance. It's also worth noting that one property, once deemed worthy, has since been removed from the list, a stark reminder that even historical significance can be a transient affair.

This [National Park Service](/National_Park_Service) list, a testament to bureaucratic diligence, is considered complete through its most recent postings on November 13, 2025. &#91;2&#93; One can only imagine the meticulous effort required to catalog these remnants of human ambition in such an expansive and often inaccessible region.

