| 1 | [Bering Expedition Landing Site](/Bering_Expedition_Landing_Site) | [[Bering Expedition Landing Site|More images]] | July 20, 1977 (#77001542) | On [Kayak Island](/Kayak_Island) <br/> 59°53′40″N 144°29′08″W / 59.89444°N 144.48556°W (Bering Expedition Landing Site) <br/> [Katalla](/Katalla,_Alaska) | One might think that simply landing on an island wouldn't merit such enduring recognition, but then, most people weren't embarking on a perilous voyage of discovery into the unknown. The [Bering Expedition Landing Site](/Bering_Expedition_Landing_Site) on [Kayak Island](/Kayak_Island) commemorates the precise location where members of [Vitus Bering](/Vitus_Bering)'s second Kamchatka expedition, under the command of Aleksei Chirikov, first set foot on Alaskan soil in 1741. This event, occurring on July 20, 1741, marked the initial documented European contact with the mainland of [Alaska](/Alaska), a moment of profound historical significance that irrevocably altered the course of the region's future. The expedition sought fresh water and a brief respite from the relentless Pacific, inadvertently claiming a vast, unforgiving territory for the Russian Empire. This site, a testament to the audacious spirit of exploration and the brutal realities of maritime discovery, was appropriately listed on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on July 20, 1977. Its isolation on [Kayak Island](/Kayak_Island), off the coast near [Katalla](/Katalla,_Alaska), only emphasizes the sheer scale of the journey undertaken. |
| 2 | [Cape Hinchinbrook Light Station](/Cape_Hinchinbrook_Light_Station) | [[Cape Hinchinbrook Light Station|More images]] | July 29, 2005 (#05000728) | Southwestern end of [Hinchinbrook Island](/Hinchinbrook_Island) <br/> • 60°14′14″N 146°38′48″W / 60.23734°N 146.64665°W (Cape Hinchinbrook Light Station) <br/> [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) | Perched precariously on the southwestern extremity of [Hinchinbrook Island](/Hinchinbrook_Island), the [Cape Hinchinbrook Light Station](/Cape_Hinchinbrook_Light_Station) stands as a stoic sentinel against the often-treacherous waters of the [Gulf of Alaska](/Gulf_of_Alaska). Originally established in 1910, this lighthouse, an indispensable aid to navigation, guided countless vessels through the notoriously difficult approaches to Prince William Sound and the port of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska). The current concrete tower, erected in 1934, replaced an earlier structure that succumbed to the relentless elements, a poetic reminder of nature's ultimate dominion. Its robust, art deco-inspired architecture, designed to withstand the region's brutal storms, reflects a pragmatic beauty born of necessity. The station's remote location meant that its keepers endured profound isolation, a common theme in the annals of Alaskan history. It was recognized for its enduring service and architectural integrity, earning its place on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on July 29, 2005. |
| 3 | [Cape St. Elias Lighthouse](/Cape_St._Elias_Light) | [[Cape St. Elias Lighthouse|More images]] | December 18, 1975 (#75002157) | Southwestern end of [Kayak Island](/Kayak_Island) <br/> • 59°47′54″N 144°35′56″W / 59.79844°N 144.59897°W (Cape St. Elias Lighthouse) <br/> [Katalla](/Katalla,_Alaska) | Another beacon of civilization's desperate grasp on the wilderness, the [Cape St. Elias Lighthouse](/Cape_St._Elias_Light) dominates the southwestern tip of [Kayak Island](/Kayak_Island), not far from the aforementioned Bering landing site. Commissioned in 1916, this formidable concrete tower was constructed to warn mariners of the dangerous, submerged reefs and the often-tempestuous weather systems that converge at this exposed point in the [Gulf of Alaska](/Gulf_of_Alaska). Its construction was a monumental undertaking, requiring vast resources and human tenacity in a virtually uninhabited region accessible only by sea. The lighthouse, a striking square tower rising from a keeper's dwelling, projects a beam that once sliced through the perpetual gloom and fog, providing a vital lifeline for shipping navigating between Prince William Sound and the open ocean. Its listing on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on December 18, 1975, acknowledges its critical role in maritime safety and its sheer architectural resilience. It remains a stark monument to the human desire for order in a chaotic world. |
| 4 | [Chilkat Oil Company Refinery Site](/Chilkat_Oil_Company_Refinery_Site) | | September 6, 1974 (#74002320) | Along Katalla Slough, about 2.7 miles (4.3 km) east of [Katalla](/Katalla,_Alaska) <br/> • 60°11′15″N 144°27′02″W / 60.18737°N 144.45047°W (Chilkat Oil Company Refinery Site) <br/> [Katalla](/Katalla,_Alaska) | The remnants of the [Chilkat Oil Company Refinery Site](/Chilkat_Oil_Company_Refinery_Site), situated along Katalla Slough approximately 2.7 miles (4.3 km) east of [Katalla](/Katalla,_Alaska), serve as a ghostly echo of [Alaska](/Alaska)'s fleeting oil boom. This site represents one of the earliest attempts at commercial oil production in [Alaska](/Alaska), with operations beginning around 1902. The Chilkat Oil Company, despite its ambitious name, faced insurmountable challenges in the remote, unforgiving landscape. The refinery processed crude oil extracted from nearby wells, producing kerosene, gasoline, and other petroleum products for local consumption. However, logistical nightmares, harsh weather, and the eventual depletion of accessible oil reserves led to its inevitable demise. Today, only scattered ruins, foundations, and rusted equipment remain, slowly being reclaimed by the Alaskan wilderness. It's a poignant reminder that not all dreams of industrial prosperity find fertile ground in this part of the world. The site was listed on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on September 6, 1974, recognizing its significance as a pioneer in the Alaskan petroleum industry, a venture that ultimately proved to be ahead of its time, or perhaps, simply too optimistic. |
| 5 | [Cordova Post Office and Courthouse](/Cordova_Post_Office_and_Courthouse) | [[Cordova Post Office and Courthouse|More images]] | August 2, 1977 (#77001571) | 612 2nd Street <br/> • 60°32′39″N 145°45′24″W / 60.54411°N 145.75662°W (Cordova Post Office and Courthouse) <br/> [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) | The [Cordova Post Office and Courthouse](/Cordova_Post_Office_and_Courthouse), located at 612 2nd Street in the heart of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska), stands as a testament to the aspirations of a burgeoning Alaskan town in the early 20th century. Constructed in 1913, this substantial two-story building in the [Federal Revival style](/Federal_Revival_architecture) was designed to house the essential federal services for the community. It served as both a post office, the vital link for communication with the outside world, and a courthouse, administering the rudimentary justice required in a frontier town. The building's solid masonry construction and classical detailing reflected a sense of permanence and governmental authority, a stark contrast to the often-ephemeral nature of other frontier settlements. It was a hub of civic life, witnessing the ebb and flow of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska)'s fortunes, from the boom years of the Copper River & Northwestern Railway to the later challenges of a declining fishing industry. Listed on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on August 2, 1977, it remains an integral part of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska)'s architectural and historical landscape, a reminder that even in remote [Alaska](/Alaska), the machinery of government grinds on. |
| 6 | [Million Dollar Bridge](/Million_Dollar_Bridge) | [[Million Dollar Bridge|More images]] | March 31, 2000 (#00000293) | Mile 48 of [Copper River Highway](/Copper_River_Highway), about 35 miles (56 km) northeast of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) <br/> • 60°40′23″N 144°44′45″W / 60.6731°N 144.74583°W (Million Dollar Bridge) <br/> [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) | The aptly, if somewhat dramatically, named [Million Dollar Bridge](/Million_Dollar_Bridge) is a marvel of early 20th-century engineering, situated at Mile 48 of the [Copper River Highway](/Copper_River_Highway), approximately 35 miles (56 km) northeast of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska). Officially known as the Miles Glacier Bridge, this steel cantilever bridge was constructed between 1909 and 1910 as a crucial component of the Copper River and Northwestern Railway. Its purpose was singular: to transport copper ore from the rich mines at Kennecott to the port of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska). The cost of its construction, an astronomical sum for its time, truly earned it its popular moniker. Spanning the formidable Copper River, it faced immense challenges, not least of which was the dynamic glacial environment that continually threatened its foundations. The bridge famously suffered a partial collapse during the 1964 Good Friday Earthquake, rendering it impassable for decades, a testament to nature's ultimate destructive power. Despite this, sections of the bridge were later repaired, allowing limited vehicular access. Its listing on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on March 31, 2000, recognizes its significance as a monumental engineering achievement and a symbol of [Alaska](/Alaska)'s industrial pioneering spirit. It's a grand, decaying monument to human perseverance and, perhaps, folly. |
| 7 | [Palugvik Archeological District](/Palugvik_Archeological_District) | | October 15, 1966 (#66000957) | [Hawkins Island](/Hawkins_Island_(Alaska)) <br/> [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) | The [Palugvik Archeological District](/Palugvik_Archeological_District), located on [Hawkins Island](/Hawkins_Island_(Alaska)) near [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska), offers a profound glimpse into the ancient human history of Prince William Sound, stretching back millennia. This district encompasses a series of shell middens and habitation sites that provide invaluable evidence of the prehistoric occupation by the Chugach Alutiiq people. Archaeological excavations at Palugvik have unearthed a wealth of artifacts, including tools, weapons, and ceremonial objects, which have allowed researchers to reconstruct the lifeways, subsistence patterns, and cultural evolution of the region's indigenous inhabitants over several thousand years. The stratified deposits reveal a continuous sequence of occupation, demonstrating the remarkable adaptability and resilience of these early communities in a challenging coastal environment. It's a place where the echoes of ancient lives are tangibly present, if one bothers to listen. Recognized as a [National Historic Landmark](/National_Historic_Landmark) and listed on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on October 15, 1966, the [Palugvik Archeological District](/Palugvik_Archeological_District) is a critical resource for understanding the deep human history of [Alaska](/Alaska), far predating any European arrival. |
| 8 | [Pioneer Igloo Hall Number 19](/Pioneer_Igloo_Hall_Number_19) | | August 15, 2012 (#12000492) | 621 1st Street <br/> • 60°32′38″N 145°45′33″W / 60.54388°N 145.75912°W (Pioneer Igloo Hall Number 19) <br/> [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) | At 621 1st Street in [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) stands the [Pioneer Igloo Hall Number 19](/Pioneer_Igloo_Hall_Number_19), a structure that embodies the communal spirit and mutual support networks vital to early Alaskan settlers. This hall belongs to the Pioneers of [Alaska](/Alaska), a fraternal organization established in 1907 to aid prospectors, miners, and other early residents of the territory. These "igloos" (local chapters) provided social hubs, welfare assistance, and a sense of community in often isolated and harsh conditions. The [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) Igloo Hall, constructed in 1910, served as a gathering place for town meetings, social events, and a refuge for those in need. Its simple, functional architecture reflects the pragmatic needs of a frontier town, yet it played an indispensable role in fostering civic identity and solidarity. The building's enduring presence speaks to the strength of community bonds in the face of immense environmental and economic challenges. Its listing on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on August 15, 2012, acknowledges its role in the social and cultural development of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska), a quiet nod to the collective human effort that built this town. |
| 9 | [Red Dragon Historic District](/Red_Dragon_Historic_District) | [[Red Dragon Historic District|More images]] | August 31, 1982 (#82004899) | Roughly bounded by Lake Avenue, 1st Street and 2nd Street <br/> • 60°32′32″N 145°45′28″W / 60.54216°N 145.75781°W (Red Dragon Historic District) <br/> [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) | The [Red Dragon Historic District](/Red_Dragon_Historic_District) in [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska), roughly delineated by Lake Avenue, 1st Street, and 2nd Street, is a vibrant, if slightly faded, tableau of the town's early commercial and social life. This district, primarily comprising structures built during [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska)'s boom years in the early 20th century, captures the architectural character of a bustling frontier port. It includes a mix of commercial buildings, residences, and civic structures, many exhibiting the utilitarian yet distinct styles prevalent in Alaskan towns of that era. The district's name itself evokes a sense of bygone eras, possibly linked to an establishment or a local legend that has since faded into the mists of history. Walking through the district, one can almost hear the echoes of prospectors, fishermen, and railway workers who once frequented these streets, shaping the town's unique identity. Its inclusion on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on August 31, 1982, signifies its importance as a well-preserved example of an Alaskan commercial center, a tangible link to the tenacious spirit that forged communities in this remote territory. |
| 10 | [St. Michael the Archangel Church](/St._Michael_the_Archangel_Church_(Cordova,_Alaska)) | [[St. Michael the Archangel Church|More images]] | June 6, 1980 (#80004578) | Southern side of Lake Avenue, between 9th Street and Birch Street <br/> • 60°32′33″N 145°44′40″W / 60.54248°N 145.74431°W (St. Michael the Archangel Church) <br/> [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) | The [St. Michael the Archangel Church](/St._Michael_the_Archangel_Church_(Cordova,_Alaska)), nestled on the southern side of Lake Avenue between 9th Street and Birch Street in [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska), is a striking example of the Russian Orthodox architectural tradition in [Alaska](/Alaska). Constructed in 1925, this church serves as a spiritual and cultural anchor for the local Orthodox community, a legacy of Russian influence that predates American acquisition of [Alaska](/Alaska). The building features distinctive onion domes and a traditional cruciform plan, elements that stand out against the more pragmatic frontier architecture of the town. Beyond its architectural significance, the church has played a continuous role in the lives of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska)'s residents, particularly those of Alutiiq and Russian descent, for nearly a century. It represents the enduring faith and cultural heritage that persevered through periods of immense change and hardship in [Alaska](/Alaska). Designated a [National Historic Landmark](/National_Historic_Landmark) and listed on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on June 6, 1980, [St. Michael the Archangel Church](/St._Michael_the_Archangel_Church_(Cordova,_Alaska)) is not merely a building but a living testament to the diverse cultural tapestry that defines this remote Alaskan community. |

